english:
  title: Colophon on the Buddhist Scriptures
  author: Kang Seok-deok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Great Sage spreads compassion and generosity to awaken the bewildered multitudes. Through the promise of merit and benefit, the virtuous and the filial cannot but turn toward him. Yet his teachings, recorded in the vast ocean of the Tripitaka, sprawl without bound or shore. Thus must we select what brings most direct blessing and write it forth for contemplation, that through this we might guide wandering souls through darkness—surely not without purpose.

    We humbly reflect upon our Queen Sohaeon, whose celestial virtue was complete in every excellence. She deserved ten thousand years, yet suddenly ascended to the distant realm. The great princes, consumed with longing and bitter anguish, cried out in their unbearable sorrow: "Having failed to fulfill our filial duty, shall we also neglect to seek merit for her sake? How can we ever repay a debt as boundless as heaven itself?" They dared to petition, and His Majesty granted permission.

    Then from the Tripitaka were gathered the most sublime and supreme teachings: the Lotus Sutra, which reveals the wonder of all dharmas in the illumination of a single heart; the Amitabha Sutra, which directs the mind toward the Pure Land of ultimate bliss; the Gateway of Avalokiteshvara, where conditions and inclinations find secret accord, rendering both beings and dharma wondrous; the Brahma Net Sutra, through which all sentient beings who receive the precepts enter directly into Buddhahood; the Awakening of Faith, which establishes great faith and plants the Buddha-seed; the Earth Store Sutra, rescuing those trapped in realms of suffering; and the Compassionate Repentance, washing away the dust of defilement. All these were recorded with gold leaf and vermillion, written in exquisite script and adorned with precious gems. Upon each scroll's opening was placed an illustrated frontispiece, so that the viewer might feel reverence and longing arise without waiting to turn the pages and recite the words.

    Alas! The Buddha's teaching declares: "Mind itself is Buddha." Our Queen, being both virtuous and sage, has surely entered directly into the Great Light Treasury of the Tathagata—of this there can be no doubt. What need then of intercession or deliverance? Yet such is the filial heart: though it might benefit one's parents by the merest speck of dust or thread, it stops at nothing to achieve its aim. How much more so with these sutras—true vessels of compassion upon the ocean of suffering, bright torches illuminating the darkened path! These most precious teachings bring benefit and blessing without end. Can the response to such sincere devotion be easily reckoned?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Tripitaka (三藏) refers to the three divisions of the Buddhist canon: sutras, monastic discipline, and commentaries.'
  - key: ''
    value: Queen Sohaeon (昭憲王后) was the mother of King Seongjong of Joseon, known for her patronage of Buddhism.
  - key: ''
    value: The works mentioned—the Lotus Sutra, Amitabha Sutra, Avalokiteshvara Sutra, Brahma Net Sutra, Awakening of Faith, and Earth Store Sutra—represent major Mahayana Buddhist texts.
  - key: ''
    value: Gold leaf and vermillion were precious materials used in the production of sacred Buddhist texts, indicating the devotional quality of this commission.
